Thanks for the detailed report and screenshots!

The `</svg>` closing tag is written by the native Skia SVG device when the canvas is **destroyed** (i.e., when `canvas.Dispose()` is called). In the code sample, `managedStream.ToArray()` is called while the `using var canvas` block is still active — so the canvas hasn't been disposed yet, and the closing tag hasn't been written.

This is why `SKFileWStream` appears to work: you'd typically read the file _after_ the canvas goes out of scope.

**Workaround — use a nested `using` block so the canvas is disposed first:**

```csharp
using var managedStream = new MemoryStream();
using var stream = new SKManagedWStream(managedStream);

using (var canvas = SKSvgCanvas.Create(bounds, stream))
{
    // drawing operations here
} // canvas disposed here → </svg> is written

result.Data = managedStream.ToArray(); // now the SVG is complete
```

Could you also confirm: in your SkiaSharp 2.88.9 code, were you also calling `managedStream.ToArray()` _before_ the canvas was disposed? If the same pattern worked in 2.88.x, it may indicate a regression in how the SVG device flushes its output, and we'll investigate further.
